The booking process for personalized shuttles involves more lead time than most people anticipate. While some services offer "same-day booking," the reality is that last-minute reservations often come with significant limitations and higher costs.

Through coordinating executive travel, I've learned that 48-hour advance notice is the sweet spot for securing optimal vehicle selection and pricing. Services that promise immediate booking often subcontract to other providers, creating communication gaps and potential service inconsistencies. This became particularly evident when we had to arrange emergency travel for board members—the difference between booking 48 hours out versus 24 hours out was substantial in terms of vehicle quality and driver experience.

**Group coordination presents another layer of complexity**. When booking for multiple executives traveling together, shuttle services often split larger parties between vehicles based on their routing algorithms. What appears as a "group booking" to the customer might actually involve separate vehicles taking different routes to the same destination. I've had to explain to executives why they weren't traveling together despite booking as a group—the operational logic prioritizes efficiency over companionship.

